1. Introduction

1.1 Background and Aim

Many firms include selected key financial ratios as part of their corporate objectives. These ratios can be easily obtained from a companys financial report, giving shareholders and potential investors the ability to make informed decisions about their investment in a given company.

In general, investors focus on the earnings they can gain in the potential investment through targets profitability ratios like earning per share, dividend yield and price/earnings ratio. Among these ratios, Earnings Per Share (EPS) receives the most attention from the financial community and investors. It is used by investors as an indicator of the profitability of listed companies, making it an important tool in the decision making process for investments.

The primary aim of this Reproducible research is to investigate the influence of various financial ratios on EPS and identify the most important determinants of EPS through an econometric analysis.

Particularly, EPS describes a companys profit or loss during a reporting period, divided by the weighted average number of outstanding ordinary shares during the same reporting period. By analyzing a companys EPS over the years, it becomes apparent if the performance of the company has improved from an investors point of view. By comparing similar companies based on their EPS, conclusions about the best possible investment may be drawn.

Data

The analysis is based on the financial data (Access requires authors permit) from the RESSET database. The dataset includes data from financial reports of non-financial companies listed at Shanghai Stock Exchange, ranging from 2009 to 2018. Previously, the analysis was conducted in Stata. To increase the reproducibility and test the model robustness, this project will be performed in R.The econometric model is a panel data model which requires hypothesis testing and best model selection.

Outline

The following steps are necessary to verify the robustness of the estimation result:

  1. First, to verify the significance of the model estimators.

  2. Second, to test an additional hypothesis. H3: Company size has positive influence on earnings per share. To quantify company size, a new dependent variable is introduced: Logarithm of Total Assets.

  3. Third, to apply two new models: Heteroskedasticity-Consistent Covariance Matrix Estimation and Panel-Corrected Standard Error.

Hypotheses

Based on the results, this research is designed to test the following hypotheses using the given dataset:

Hypothesis 0: The variables under investigation do not significantly influence EPS

Hypothesis 1: Return on asset has positive influence on EPS.

Hypothesis 2: Debt to equity has negative influence on EPS.

Hypothesis 3: Logarithm of total assets has positive influence on EPS.

Definitions

The term Return on Assets (ROA) refers to a financial ratio that indicates how profitable a company is in relation to its total assets. Corporate management, analysts, and investors can use ROA to determine how efficiently a company uses its assets to generate a profit.

The term Debt to Equity ratio compares a companys total liabilities to its shareholder equity and can be used to evaluate how much leverage a company is using.

The term Total Assets is all the assets that one company owns. Included in total assets is cash, accounts receivable, inventory, equipment etc.

1.3 Model selection

First, one should choose between random and fixed effect model.

Hausmann test therefore should be used. It evaluates the consistency of an estimator when compared to an alternative, less efficient estimator which is already consistent. The alternative hypothesis assumes the mismatch of the random effects model estimator with the simultaneous consistency of the fixed effects estimator.

The null hypothesis assume that this statistic has asymptotically the chi-squared distribution with the number of degrees of freedom equal to the rank of matrix.

If the study rejects the null hypothesis, it means that \(_R\), our random effect estimator, is inconsistent. Then methods are used that do not assume that there is a correlation between individual effects and explanatory variables. So, fixed effect model is preferred and vice versa.

random <-plm(EPS~ROA+Dbequrt+LOGTA, 
             data = dataset, 
             index = c("CompanyCode", "year"), 
             model = "random")

Since the P-value from Hausman test is 0.3056. For \(\alpha = 0.05\), we can not reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, the random effect model is more accurate than the fixed effect model.

Second step would be choose between OLS and random effect model. BreuschPagan test is applied here.

The null hypothesis is that the error variances are all equal and OLS model should be selected.

OLS <-plm(EPS~ROA+Dbequrt+LOGTA, 
          data = dataset, 
          index = c("CompanyCode", "year"), 
          model = "pooling")

The p-value resulting from Breusch-Pagan test is \(0.00000000000000022\). Thus, for \(\alpha = 0.05\), we should reject the null hypothesis. Therefore individual effect is significant and random effect model is preferred than OLS model. We should evaluate random effect model compared to the other two models.

1.4 Estimation and diagnostic tests

# Testing for serial correlation
pbgtest(random)
## 
##  Breusch-Godfrey/Wooldridge test for serial correlation in panel models
## 
## data:  EPS ~ ROA + Dbequrt + LOGTA
## chisq = 802.93, df = 10, p-value < 0.00000000000000022
## alternative hypothesis: serial correlation in idiosyncratic errors

Since the P-value from Breusch-Godfrey/Wooldridge test is \(0.00000000000000022\). For \(\alpha = 0.05\), we should reject the null hypothesis (there is not serial correlation issue). Therefore there is a serial correlation issue from the estimated random model.

# Testing for heteroskedasticity
bptest(EPS~ROA+Dbequrt+LOGTA, 
       data = dataset, 
       studentize = TRUE)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  EPS ~ ROA + Dbequrt + LOGTA
## BP = 136.12, df = 3, p-value < 0.00000000000000022

Since the P-value from Breusch-Pagan test is \(0.00000000000000022\). For \(\alpha = 0.05\), we should reject the null hypothesis. Therefore there is a heteroskedasticity problem from the estimated random model besides the serial correlation problem. According to MacKinnon J. G., White H. (1985),Heteroskedasticity-Consistent Covariance Matrix Estimation method might solve there problems.

# Controlling for heteroskedasticity and autocorrelation:
Robust <- coeftest(fixed, 
                   vcov. = vcovHC(fixed, 
                                  method = "white1", 
                                  type = "HC0", 
                                  cluster = "group"))

Also Panel-Corrected Standard Error(PCSE) method can also solve these issues and allow for better inference from estimated model shown by Delia Bailey, Jonathan N. Katz.

lm_pcse <- lm(EPS~ROA + Dbequrt + LOGTA, 
              data = dataset)

PCSE <- pcse(lm_pcse,
             groupN = dataset$CompanyCode, 
             groupT = dataset$year)

The above table presents the regression result step by step with pooled ordinary least squared (POLS), fixed effect (FE), random effect (RE), and random effect model with robust standard error. Since the existing of heteroskedasticity and autocorrelation issues, random effect model with robust Standard Error method should be made for this model. This study will focus on its result and compare the differences among other models.

Random effect with robust standard error model regression shows that the ROA has p-value of 0.002 (0.002 < 0.01). So, at the significance level of 0.05, ROA has positive influence on earnings per share. If ROA increases by one unit and other variables stay the same, EPS will increase by 0.06. In the previous research R. Bratamanggala concludes, that ROA has significant effect on EPS as well. Their analysis is focusing on the Indonesia manufacturing sector using companies listed in the Indonesian Stock Exchange.

Debt to Equity has p-value of 0.00001 (0.00001 < 0.01). So, at the significance level of 0.01, debt to equity has negative influence on earnings per share. If Debt to Equity increases by one unit and other variables stay the same, EPS will decrease by 0.0001. Debt to Equity represents companies capital structure. A higher value shows that the company uses aggressive financing policy. Normally, as firms apply more debt, the firm looses its capacity to gain profit because of high interest. However, in the previous research done by Bratamanggala and Khalaf, they also find a positive correlation between Debt to Equity and EPS. The reason behind it might be that the debt can support short term liquidity issue and long-term growth for the firm. In this research, Debt to equity has negative influence over earnings per share.

Logarithm of Total Asset has p-value of 0.009 (0.009< 0.01). So, at the significance level of 0.01, logarithm of total asset (company size) has positive influence on EPS. If LOGTA increases by one percent and other variables stay the same, EPS will increase by 0.092.

The result of R-squared is 0.589 for random effect regression. This model might explain the changes of earnings per share up to 0.589 and the rest is influenced by other variables which are not discussed in this research. The other regressions also provide similar results. All variables in different models pasted t-test at significance level of 0.01.

3. Conclusion

This research is conducted to verify the empirical evidence about the influence of financial ratios and company size on earnings per share partially and simultaneously on listed a share companies at Shanghai Stock Exchange from 2009 to 2018.

The results obtained are:

  • Return on asset has positive and significant influence on earnings per share.

  • Debt to equity has negative influence on earnings per share.

  • Logarithm of Total Assets has positive influence on earnings per share.

The research conclusion can be the basis for investors to evaluate one companys performance. For companys manager board, it can also be applied to diagnose the companys financial situation and set up strategy to increase its earnings. For the research sample, the traditional financial analysis still plays a key role in evaluating ones performance, especially, the profitability and leveraging ratio. A company that can constantly generate desired earnings and use leverage wisely will growth healthily and preferred by investors. Also because of economies of scale, a bigger company size will also benefit the company.

Since the R-squared value is not high in this research, there are might be other information that could affect firms return. For example, political situation and policy, technical situation and macroeconomic condition could be good variables adding to the financial ratios that this research chosen. Also, due to the limit of data, this research only takes 10 years data from A share companies listed at Shanghai Stock exchange. A similar research on another country is recommended.

1. Reproducible Research on The Effect of Financial Ratios towards Earnings per Share

1.1 Research background and goal

Many firms have selected key financial ratios from financial report, such as profitability ratios (Margin), to be included as part of their corporate objectives.

In general, investors focus on the earnings they can gain in the potential investment through targets profitability ratios like earning per share, dividend yield and price/earnings ratio. Among these ratios,earnings per share receives much more attention from the financial community and investors. As a good indicator of the profitability for any listed companies, it is a widely used by investors in decision making for investments.

earnings per share (EPS) is an entitys profit or loss that is attributable to ordinary shareholders for a reporting period divided by the weighted average number of outstanding ordinary shares during the reporting period.

By tracking a firms earnings per share by years, people can find whether the performance of the firm is improved or not.

By comparing similar firms earnings per share, one can find firms of better earning power and invest in such firms.

The main goal of this Reproducible research is to verify the influence of potential financial ratio on earnings per share and identify other important determinants of earnings per share by the means of econometric analysis based on financial data (Due to data protection act, dataset can be shared only through this Onedrive link after acquiring authors permit) from 2009 to 2018, derived from the financial statements of non-financial companies listed at Shanghai Stock Exchange in RESSET database. The previous analysis was conducted in Stata. To increase the reproducibility and test the model robustness, this project will be performed in R.

The econometric model is a panel data model which requires hypothesis testing and best model selection. The following steps are necessary to verify the robustness of the estimation result:

  1. First, to verify the significance of the model estimators.

  2. Second, to add a new hypothesis No.3: Company size has positive influence on earnings per share. A new dependent variable: Logarithm of Total Assets in order to represent a given companys size and check for consistency.

  3. Third, to apply two new models: Heteroskedasticity-Consistent Covariance Matrix Estimation and Panel-Corrected Standard Error.

Based on the results, this research is designed to verify following hypothesis using the given dataset:

Hypothesis 1: Return on asset has positive influence on earnings per share.

Hypothesis 2: Debt to equity has negative influence on earnings per share.

Hypothesis 3:(New added in this research) Logarithm of Total Assets (Company size measurement) has positive influence on earnings per share.

for those who have no experience in financial statements field:

The term return on assets(ROA) refers to a financial ratio that indicates how profitable a company is in relation to its total assets. Corporate management, analysts, and investors can use ROA to determine how efficiently a company uses its assets to generate a profit.

The term debt to equity ratio compares a companys total liabilities to its shareholder equity and can be used to evaluate how much leverage a company is using.

The term Total Assets is all the assets that one entity owns. Included in total assets is cash, accounts receivable, inventory, equipment etc.

hist(dataset$EPS, xlab = "EPS")

R psych package has great advantage in the data visualization. The graphs below show the correlation and distribution for the dataset.

Analysing the graphs from last row, there is a positive trend for ROA and EPS, weak negative trend for Debt to equity and EPS and almost flat linear relationship for Logarithm of Total Assets and EPS.

pairs.panels(dataset[c("ROA", "Dbequrt", "LOGTA",

Next step will be select the most appropriate model.

1.3 Model selection

First, one should choose between random and fixed effect model.

Hausmann test therefore should be used.It evaluates the consistency of an estimator when compared to an alternative, less efficient estimator which is already consistent. The alternative hypothesis assumes the mismatch of the random effects model estimator with the simultaneous consistency of the fixed effects estimator.

The null hypothesis assume that this statistic has asymptotically the chi-squared distribution with the number of degrees of freedom equal to the rank of matrix.

If the study rejects the null hypothesis, it means that _RE, our random effect estimator, is inconsistent. Then methods are used that do not assume that there is a correlation between individual effects and explanatory variables. So, fixed effect model is preferred and vice versa.

random <-plm(EPS~ROA+Dbequrt+LOGTA, data=dataset, 
             index=c("CompanyCode", "year"), model="random")

Since the P-value from Hausman test is 0.3056. For \(\alpha = 0.05\), we can not reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, the random effect model is more accurate than the fixed effect model.

Second step would be choose between OLS and random effect model.BreuschPagan test is applied here.

The null hypothesis is that the error variances are all equal and OLS model should be selected.

OLS <-plm(EPS~ROA+Dbequrt+LOGTA, data=dataset, 
          index=c("CompanyCode", "year"), model="pooling")

The p-value resulting from Breusch-Pagan test is 0.00000000000000022. Thus, for \(\alpha = 0.05\), we should reject the null hypothesis. Therefore individual effect is significant and random effect model is preferred than OLS model. We should evaluate random effect model compared to the other two models.

1.4 Estimation and diagnostic tests

# Testing for serial correlation
pbgtest(random)
## 
##  Breusch-Godfrey/Wooldridge test for serial correlation in panel models
## 
## data:  EPS ~ ROA + Dbequrt + LOGTA
## chisq = 802.93, df = 10, p-value < 0.00000000000000022
## alternative hypothesis: serial correlation in idiosyncratic errors

Since the P-value from Breusch-Godfrey/Wooldridge test is 0.00000000000000022. For \(\alpha = 0.05\), we should reject the null hypothesis (there is not serial correlation issue). Therefore there is a serial correlation issue from the estimated random model.

# Testing for heteroskedasticity
bptest(EPS~ROA+Dbequrt+LOGTA, data=dataset, studentize=TRUE)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  EPS ~ ROA + Dbequrt + LOGTA
## BP = 136.12, df = 3, p-value < 0.00000000000000022

Since the P-value from Breusch-Pagan test is 0.00000000000000022. For \(\alpha = 0.05\), we should reject the null hypothesis. Therefore there is a heteroskedasticity problem from the estimated random model besides the serial correlation problem. According to MacKinnon J. G., White H. (1985),Heteroskedasticity-Consistent Covariance Matrix Estimation method might solve there problems.

# Controlling for heteroskedasticity and autocorrelation:
Robust <- coeftest(fixed, vcov. = vcovHC(fixed, method="white1", type="HC0", cluster="group"))

Also Panel-Corrected Standard Error(PCSE) method can also solve these issues and allow for better inference from estimated model shown by Delia Bailey, Jonathan N. Katz.

lm_pcse <- lm(EPS~ROA + Dbequrt + LOGTA, data = dataset)
PCSE <- pcse(lm_pcse,groupN = dataset$CompanyCode, groupT =dataset$year)
summary(PCSE)

The above table presents the regression result step by step with pooled ordinary least squared (POLS), fixed effect (FE), random effect (RE), and random effect model with robust standard error. Since the existing of heteroskedasticity and autocorrelation issues, random effect model with robust Standard Error method should be made for this model. This study will focus on its result and compare the differences among other models.

Random effect with robust standard error model regression shows that the ROA has p-value of 0.002 (0.002 < 0.01). So, at the significance level of 0.05, return on asset has positive influence on earnings per share. If ROA increases by one unit and other variables stay the same, EPS will increase by 0.06. In the previous research **R. Bratamanggala* conclude that return on asset has significant effect over earnings per share as well. Their analysis is focusing on the Indonesia manufacturing sector using companies listed in the Indonesian Stock Exchange.

Debt to Equity has p-value of 0.00001 (0.00001 < 0.01). So, at the significance level of 0.01, debt to equity has negative influence on earnings per share. If Debt to Equity increases by one unit and other variables stay the same, EPS will decrease by 0.0001. Debt to Equity represents companys capital structure. A higher value shows that the company uses aggressively financing policy. Normally, as firms apply more debt, the firm losses its capacity to gain profit because of high interest. However, in the previous research done by R. Bratamanggala and Khalaf , they also find a positive correlation between Debt to Equity and earnings per share. The reason behind it might be that the debt can support short term liquidity issue and long-term growth for the firm. In this research, Debt to equity has negative influence over earnings per share.

Logarithm of Total Asset has p-value of 0.009 (0.009< 0.01). So, at the significance level of 0.01, logarithm of total asset (company size) has positive influence on earnings per share. If LOGTA increases by one percent and other variables stay the same, EPS will increase by 0.092.

The result of R-squared is 0.589 for random effect regression. This model might explain the changes of earnings per share up to 0.589 and the rest is influenced by other variables which are not discussed in this research. The other regressions also provide similar results. All variables in different models pasted t-test at significance level of 0.01.

3. Conclusion

This research is conducted to verify the empirical evidence about the influence of financial ratios and company size on earnings per share partially and simultaneously on listed a share companies at Shanghai Stock Exchange from 2009 to 2018.

The results obtained are:

  • Return on asset has positive and significant influence on earnings per share.

  • Debt to equity has negative influence on earnings per share.

  • Logarithm of Total Assets has positive influence on earnings per share.

The research conclusion can be the basis for investors to evaluate one companys performance. For companys manager board, it can also be applied to diagnose the companys financial situation and set up strategy to increase its earnings. For the research sample, the traditional financial analysis still plays a key role in evaluating ones performance, especially, the profitability and leveraging ratio. A company that can constantly generate desired earnings and use leverage wisely will growth healthily and preferred by investors. Also because of economies of scale, a bigger company size will also benefit the company.

Since the R-squared value is not high in this research, there are might be other information that could affect firms return. For example, political situation and policy, technical situation and macroeconomic condition could be good variables adding to the financial ratios that this research chosen. Also, due to the limit of data, this research only takes 10 years data from A share companies listed at Shanghai Stock exchange. A similar research on another country is recommended.
